%I A123448 #35 Jul 04 2026 18:53:51
%S A123448 1,2,4,11,33,142,776,5699,50723,524572,6037518,75912033,1029974969,
%T A123448 14974215412
%N A123448 Number of permutation perfect graphs on n nodes.
%C A123448 All permutation graphs are perfect. - _Jakub Jablonski_, Sep 07 2020
%C A123448 From _Bartlomiej Pawlik_, Jun 22 2026: (Start)
%C A123448 The graph G[p] of a permutation p, has {1,2,...,n} as its vertex set with i and j being adjacent if and only if (i,j) is an inversion; i.e., (i-j)*(p(i)-p(j)) < 0.
%C A123448 A graph G is a permutation graph if there is a permutation p such that G is isomorphic to G[p]. (End)
%H A123448 S. Hougardy, <a href="http://www.or.uni-bonn.de/~hougardy/">Home Page</a>
%H A123448 S. Hougardy, <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.disc.2006.05.021">Classes of perfect graphs</a>, Discr. Math. 306 (2006), 2529-2571.
%e A123448 a(3) = 4 because there are four unlabeled permutation graphs on three vertices: the empty graph, the graph with one edge and one isolated vertex, the path P_3, and the complete graph K_3. For example, using the permutations 123, 213, 231, and 321 gives respectively these four graphs. - _Bartlomiej Pawlik_, Jun 22 2026
%K A123448 nonn,more,hard
